===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}

The formation is unclear. The base component is consistently {{zh-l|*丙}}; late-period variants add {{zh-l|*口}} below. The element placed atop {{zh-l|*丙}} varies:

# Inverted triangle with a horizontal bar.
# {{zh-l|*辛}}-like form: as type 1, but the tip extends a vertical stroke downward to {{zh-l|*丙}}, with the bar crossing this stroke.
# Bare inverted triangle (▽); possibly the original form of {{zh-l|*樴}}.
# Two instances of type 1 or 2, placed symmetrically left and right.
# Paired round or teardrop-shaped elements, each trailing a stroke down toward {{zh-l|*丙}}.
# {{zh-l|*辛}}-form with star-shaped marks in its quadrants (two or four); possibly a dedicated graph for the Shāng star.

In oracle bone and early Western Zhou bronze script, {{zh-l|*賞}} is written as {{zh-l|*商}} over {{zh-l|*貝}}; by mid-Western Zhou the upper part is replaced by {{zh-l|*尚}}.

===Etymology===
;dynasty's name
:The original semantics are uncertain. Early inscriptions often use {{och-l|商|tr=*staŋ}} for later {{och-l|賞|tr=*staŋh}}, suggesting an older sense related to marking out, recognizing, or manifesting, before the narrower sense “reward”. It is also worth comparing {{och-l|章|tr=*taŋ}} / {{och-l|彰|tr=*taŋ}} (“mark; manifest”) and {{och-l|尚|tr=*daŋh}} / {{zh-l|上|tr=*daŋh}} (“raised; above”), which may point to an earlier notion of something conspicuous or elevated. Huayuanzhuang East collocations such as {{zh-l|奏商}}, {{zh-l|學商}}, and {{zh-l|舞商}} are especially noteworthy and may reflect a specialized late-Shang ritual or performative use.

;“to trade” → “trader, merchant” 
:From {{och-l|賒}} plus terminative suffix *''-ŋ'' ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}}). See there for further etymology.

;“to discuss”
:Semantically derived from sense “to trade” ({{zh-ref|Schuessler, 2007}})

